 Geoderma, 26 (1981) 13-23                                                        13  Elsevier Scientific Publishing Company, Amsterdam -- Printed in The Netherlands    DETECTING INFILTRATION OF WATER THROUGH SOIL CRACKS BY  TIME-DOMAIN REFLECTOMETRY*1    G.C. TOPP and J.L. DAVIS.2  Land Resource Research Institute, Agriculture Canada, Ottawa, Ont., KIA 0C6 (Canada)  Geophysics and Geochemistry Division, Geological Survey of Canada, Ottawa, Ont.  KIA OE8 (Canada)  (Received February 1, 1980; accepted November 11, 1980~    ABSTRACT  Topp, G.C. and Davis, J.L., 1981. Detecting infiltration of water through soil cracks by  time-domain reflectometry. Geoderma, 26: 13--23.  During an experiment where simulated rainfall was applied to cracked soil, time-domain  reflectometry (TDR) was used to measure the water content of cracks and adjacent soil  vs. water content at some distance from the cracks. At a depth of 10 to 30 cm the rate of  wetting of soil immediately adjacent to the cracks was more ~ apid than that of the soil at  some distance from the cracks. Independent predictions of when water should begin  flowing down the cracks were deduced from knowledge of the applied "rainfall" rate,  field-measured hydraulic conductivity, initial water content and bulk density. These pre-  dictions checked well with those TDR measurements which indicated when water began  to accumulate in and adjacent to the cracks in a clay soil under corn and soybeans. More  than 1 cm of rainfall at rates greater than 0.1 cm/h contributed water to the soil cracks.  The water content profiles showed the very limited depth of wetting in the soil at some  distance away from the cracks as opposed to the much greater depth of wetting within  and adjacent to the cracks.  INTRODUCTION  Cracks or large pores in soil play a significant role in the distribution of  rainwater within the soil. The distribution of water entering the soil body is  of great importance in relation to plant water supply and also in relation to  solute transport of surface and subsurface water. Shuford et al. (1977) have  shown in infiltration experiments that large pores represent major pathways  for the trangmittance of nitrates and chlorides in the applied water. Bolton  et al. (1970) reported that in Brookston clay soil, subsurface drains carried  more water and nutrients from corn plots than from blue-grass sod or other  crops in rotations. From later experiments on the same type of soil, the rate  of response to rainfall of subsurface drains at two depths indicated that cracks    ,1 L.R.R.I. Contribution No. 20  ,2 Current address: Ensco Inc., Springfield, Va. (U.S.A.)    0016-7061/81/0000--0000/$02.50 1981 Elsevier Scientific Publishing Company    14    or large pores were operative in conducting rainwater to the drains (Bolton  and Hore, 1976).  Soil cracks, as major components in the water transport network, make  mathematical analysis of water flow in such soils virtually impossible. Even  so, a better understanding of the role of cracks in the water transport will  clarify the limits of current mathematical approaches and perhaps indicate  new directions.  The object of the experiments reported here was to demonstrate that  time-domain reflectometry (TDR) techniques can be used to measure the  occurrence of water in soil cracks and adjacent soil at greater depth and in  greater amounts than that accumulating in the main body of the soil during  simulated rainfall conditions. The field measured hydraulic conductivity  obtained with the air-entry permeameter (Topp and Binns, 1976) crust-top  permeameter (Bouma and Denning, 1972) and initial soil parameters such as  water content and bulk density were used to make independent predictions  of when water was expected to flow to the cracks. The results of the two  techniques are compared and discussed.  I~fATERIALS AND METHODS  Soil, sites and infiltration procedure  Three infiltration trials were conducted on each of two sites in Brookston  clay in Essex County, southwest Ontario, Canada. The crops grown on the  two sites were soybeans and corn. The experiment,,~ were conducted in late  summer {August 1976) after dehydration of the clay soil by evapotranspira-  tion had opened up numerous cracks ranging in width up to 5 cm at the sur-  face.  The infiltration trials took place within a 76 cm diameter region enclosed  by a galvanized steel ring which was hammered 4 cm into the soil leaving 6 cm  above the soil. Three infiltration rings (A, B and C) were installed between  corn rows and three rings (D, E and F) were instal]ted with a row of soybeans    "~ ,,~TRANSMISSION  LINE  "'3        I\~          INFILTRATION  C R A C K "~.~.j~~.~.p"~ GUAR D RING   -- x   '~                 -~  Fig. 1. Layout of infiltration ring showing location of the four transmission lines relative  to the crack.    15    passing within the ring. All locations were chosen to have a significant crack  passing across each ring as shown in Fig. 1.  During a four hour period simulated rainfe]l was added to give a total ac-  cumulated water depth of 2.5 cm. The rainfall rate was varied according to a  half cycle of a sine function as depicted in F'~. 2. This pattern and amount  approximated a once-in-five-year precipitation event. The water was applied  in measured volume increments which corresponded to 15-min time intervals.  The simulated rainfall was applied in a fine spray from a hand sprayer over  the first half of each 15-min interval. The TDR measurements for soil water  content were carried out during the second half of the interval as described  below.  TIME-DOMAIN    REFLECTOMETER  '  '  '  I  '  '  '  I  '  '  '  I  '  '  '              r"  .9                               TIMING ~, DISPLAY I  .e                                                 UNIT  .6                                 2.4           GENERATOR      RECEIVER  Alpplcation                                               Water                           _!. 