continuities were placed at 10, 30 and 60 cm depths. The increments over  which water content was determined were 0 to 10 cm, 10 to 30 cm, 30 to  60 cm and 60 to 110 cm. The major part of the electromagnetic field was  confined to an elliptical cross-section where the rods are the verticles of the  ellipse. Thus the measured sample was of elliptical cross-section and &gt; 20 X l  cm3 where l is the length of the transmission line section.  The profile of water content with depth was determined at four locations  and at various times in each ring from the transmission lines placed vertically  in the soil as follows' one in a soil crack, one near the soil crack (about 5 cm  away), and two in the uncracked portion of the soil as shown in Fig. 1. The  cracks in the soil were not straight to a depth of 110 cm, the length of the  transmission lines, thus it was impossible to keep the rods solely in cracks  or to determine for certain that the rods near the cracks did not eventually  enter a crack at some depth. Measurements of soil-water content versus depth  were taken once before any infiltration, five times during infiltration and up  to three times after termination of infiltration. Each TDR measurement took  about two minutes accounting for set up time and checking. The TDR oscillo.  scope was photographed using a polaroid camera. The travel times were mea-  sured from each photograph and the apparent dielectric constant, Ka, was  calculated following Davis et al. {1977) and Topp et al. (1980). The empirical  equation:  2  Ka = 2.26 + 17.60v + 1060v                  (1)  given by Davis et al. (1977) for four different soils was used to determine the  corresponding volumetric water content, 0 v, for each measured Ka.  Attempts were made to validate eq. 1 for this soil by gravimetric sampling  immediately following the last electrical measurement. The soil samples were  taken from within the transmission lines i.e. between the rods inserted in  the soil. Sample volumes and thus densities were uncertain as a result of  sample breakage in dry samples or compaction of wetted soil. Thus a direct  comparison of electrical and gravimetric water content was impossible. It  was assumed that within the cultivated layer (0--20 cm) and away from  cracks the soil was of uniform density. A linear regression of 0 v from eq. 1  on 0w by gravimetric sampling gave standard error of estimates of 3.3% for  the corn field and 3.8% for the soybean field. Because these errors of esti-  mate are much larger than those found by Davis et al. {1977} and Topp et    17    al. {1980) it was concluded that the variability of measured density con-  tributed much more error than did eq. 1.    Hydraulic conductivity and estimation of iufiltrability    The hydraulic conductivity of the surface soil was measured to provide  data for estimating the infiltrability of the non-cracked soil and thus another  estimate of when the added water would flow to the soil cracks. The air-  entry permeameter (Topp and Binns, 1976} was used to determine the satu-  rated hydraulic conductivity of the soil early in the growing season before  cracks developed. Later as cracks began to appear, the unsaturated hydraulic  conductivity was determined at several negative pressure heads using the  crust-top permeameter (Bouma and Denning, 1972}.  Observations at the locations of the infiltration rings indicated that there  was about 2 cm of crumbly soil material on the surface of the essentially  unstructured soil between the cracks. It was assumed that, on addition of  water to the soil surface, the crumbly surface soil wetted to 85% of satura-  tion without restricting the infiltration rate. The quantity of water which  was added in this way was obtained by subtraction of the initial water con-  tent as measured by TDR and selected gravimetric sampling from 85% of the  saturated value. After sufficient water had been added to wet the surface  2 cm, we assumed the rate of infiltration was equal to the measured saturated  hydraulic conductivity. The applied rainfall rate in excess of this infiltration  rate was assumed to flow to the cracks in addition to that already there  directly from the rainfall intercepted by the exposed crack area. Thus, it was  possible to estimate not only when water began flowing to the cracks but  also the quantity which was in excess of the infiltrability of the soil.  By observing the soil surface during the application of the "rainfall" it was  possible to estimate when free water appeared. The appearance of free water  was interpreted as the time when the "rainfall" rate exceeded the infiltra-  bility of soil. This time was recorded as a third measure of when water was  expected to flow to the cracks.    RESULTS AND DISCUSSION    To determine when water appeared in the soil cracks as a result of the ap-  plied "rain" it was advantageous to compare rates of wetting in the different  depth intervals. Fig. 4 and 5 show the average change of water content, A0 v,  for three depth increments 0--10, 10--30, and 30--110 cm from the trans-  mission lines some distance away from the cracks and from the lines in the  cracks.  Under both corn and soybeans the top 10 cm showed similar rates of  wetting, and slightly more water was measured some distance away from  the cracks than in the cracks. Although open initially, the cracks contained  some soil material which was carried there with water and by swelling but  the cracks held less water than some distance away from the cracks.    18  CORN FIELD  0 3!   ~.~~~_~.._~SOYBEAN   FIELD                                                             0.30.2 1         ~~  Ao.  01~     /  yf                                                                            I     I     I     I     I     I  N    '                 i_  .....  ~     ~     ~     J  ,,u-J                           0    I     2    3    4    8    12    16  - 0   I   2   3   4   8   12   16  27                            (a)