racks slightly later, at 1.75 h after start of experiment. These  independent predictions correspond well to 1.5 to 2.25 h range estimated  from the TDR data of Figs. 6 and 7.  During the experiments, the surface soil was observed carefully for the  presence of free water. Only in ring (B) was free water not observed. The  times of first occurrence of free water at the surface ranged from 1.25 to  2.25 h. Thus, this observational method gave results similar to the other two  methods.  The data given here can be interpreted in relation to the drainage studies  reported by Bolten and Hore (1976). On the same soil type, they showed  flow in subsurface drains at 60 and 95 cm depth after rainfalls of 2.0--3.0 cm.  In addition, the rate of response of the drain flow was extremely rapid,  going from zero flow to peak flow in less than 1 h (figs. 3 and 4 in Bolton and  Hore, 1976). The time between initiation of flow at 60 cm depth and 95 cm    22    depth was less than 2 h. Such a short time would only result from water  reaching the drains by way of cracks and large pores. Our findings that water  appeared in soil cracks after addition of about 1 cm of water to the soil sur-  face is consistent with those of Bolton and Hore (1976). Both indicate that  the flow of water in soil cracks is an especially important component of the  water moving to subsurface drains.    SUMMARY AND CONCLUSIONS    The volumetric water contents measured by the TDR technique using trans-  mission lines, both in soil cracks and away from cracks, were used to estimate  when water entered the cracks. The change of water content with time in the  individual cracks at the 10--30 cm depth was the most definite indicator of  when water was entering the measured zone of the crack. Comparable esti-  mates of when water entered the soil cracks were obtained with greater  effort from the use o!~ field-measured hydraulic conductivity values, initial  water contents, and bulk density. In these experiments both methods showed  that rainfall rates in excess of 0.1 cm/hr after 1 cm had fallen contributed  to a relatively large accumulation of water in and adjacent to the cracks.  The water content profiles from the TDR technique showed that changes  in water content away from cracks were confined mostly to the top 10 cm,  whereas changes in the cracks occurred over upper 30 cm but much less in the  top 10 cm than immediately below. The sample volume, the nondestructive  nature and the simplicity of measurement with the TDR technique are advan-  tages over any other available techniques when applied to studying water  flow in soils with cracks.    ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS    The authors gratefully recognize the efforts of Keith Wires and Walter  Zebchuk during the infiltration experiments and also those of Douglas McLean  and Craig Miller for assistance with hydraulic conductivity determinations.  Dr. A.P. Annan's suggestions during execution of this project are appreciated.  The study discussed herein was carried out as part of the efforts of the In-  ternational Reference Group on Great Lakes Pollution from Land Use Activi-  ties (PLUARG), an organization of the International Joint Commission (IJC),  established under the Canada--U.S. Great Lakes Quality Agreement of 1972.  Findings and conclusions are those of the authors and do not necessarily re-  flect the views of the Reference Group or its recommendations to the Com-  mission.    REFERENCES    Bolton, E.F., Aylesworth, J.W. and Hore, F.R., 1970. Nutrient losses through tile drains  under three cropping systems and two fertility levels on a Brookston Clay soil. Can. J.  Soil Sci., 50: 275--279.    23    Bolton, E.F. and Hore, F.R., 1976. Sub-surface drainage related to agronomic factors on  Brookston Clay soil. Proc. of Specialty Conference "Environmental Impact of Irriga-  tion and Drainage, Am. Soc. Civ. Eng., New York, N.Y., pp. 221--228.  Bouma, J. and Denning, J.L., 1972. Field measurement of unsaturated hydraulic condu