                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  AbstractDuring an experiment where simulated rainfall was applied to cracked soil, time-domain reflectometry (TDR) was used to measure the water content of cracks and adjacent soil vs. water content at some distance from the cracks. At a depth of 10 to 30 cm the rate of wetting of soil immediately adjacent to the cracks was more rapid than thatof the soil at some distance from the cracks. Independent predictions of when water should begin flowing down the cracks were deduced from knowledge of the applied Ã¢Â€ÂœrainfallÃ¢Â€Â rate, field-measured hydraulic conductivity, initial water content and bulk density. These predictions checked well with those TDR measurements which indicated when water began to accumulate in and adjacent to the cracks in a clay soil under corn and soybeans. More than 1 cm of rainfall at rates greater than 0.1 cm/h contributed water to the soil cracks. The water content profiles showed the very limited depth of wetting in the soil at some distance away from the cracks as opposed to the much greater depth of wetting within and adjacent to the cracks. 